  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment (environmental-gap variant)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all meeting required levels), 6 factors not assessed (acceptable at MRL 2). The device is deployed in operating-theatre environments subject to temperature excursions (18–28°C), fluctuating ambient pressure (hypobaric transport scenarios), and electromagnetic interference from surgical imaging equipment. Validation activities were conducted exclusively under controlled laboratory conditions at 22°C and standard atmospheric pressure; no environmental-sensitivity study was performed, and the operating envelope does not formally bound temperature, pressure, or EMI parameters.",
  "assuranceLevel": "Medium",
  "decision": "Accepted",
  "couName": "CPB use",
  "deviceClass": "Class II",
  "modelRiskLevel": 2,
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/morrison-cpb-hemolysis-req-001",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cpb-hemolysis-claim-001",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/morrison-cfd-hemolysis-v2",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-cpb-lab-22c-atm-dataset",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-cpb-geometry-tolerance-sweep"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2. The pump is operated in surgical suites and during inter-facility patient transport, environments characterised by temperature variation (18–28°C), potential hypobaric conditions at altitude, and electromagnetic fields from imaging and monitoring equipment. These environmental parameters alter blood viscosity, pump priming behaviour, and sensor-driven feedback loops that govern operating-point selection.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-01-lab-22c",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Laboratory hemolysis validation at 22°C, atmospheric pressure",
      "description": "CFD predictions of relative hemolysis index compared against in-vitro measurements using bovine blood surrogate. All five flow-speed operating points tested in a temperature-controlled laboratory at 22°C ± 0.5°C and 101.3 kPa. RH predictions agreed with measured values within 8% across all operating points. No trials were conducted at temperatures outside 22°C, at reduced ambient pressures, or in the presence of electromagnetic interference sources. A single temperature sensitivity check was performed at 37°C for the nominal operating point only; no systematic environmental parametric sweep was executed, and the results of the 37°C check were not used to bound model validity across the full deployment envelope."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-02-geometry-sweep",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Geometric tolerance sweep validation",
      "description": "Five impeller-clearance and volute-width tolerance combinations simulated and compared against bench measurements. All experiments conducted at 22°C, atmospheric pressure. Confirms model sensitivity to geometric variation but does not address environmental parameter sensitivity."
    }
  ],
